  "prompt": "What is the difference between ordinary differential equations and partial differential equations?",
  "response": "Ordinary differential equations (ODEs) and partial differential equations (PDEs) are both types of differential equations, which are mathematical equations that relate a function to its derivatives. The main difference between them lies in the type of functions they deal with and the type of derivatives involved.\n\n1. **Ordinary Differential Equations (ODEs):**\n   - ODEs involve functions of a single independent variable, typically denoted as \\( t \\) or \\( x \\).\n   - The derivatives in ODEs are ordinary derivatives, meaning they are taken with respect to this single independent variable.\n   - ODEs are used to model phenomena that change with respect to one variable, such as time in the case of population growth or distance in the case of a falling object.\n   - An example of an ODE is \\( \\frac{dy}{dt} = ky \\), which describes exponential growth or decay.\n\n2. **Partial Differential Equations (PDEs):**\n   - PDEs involve functions of multiple independent variables, such as \\( x \\), \\( y \\), and \\( z \\) in three-dimensional space, or \\( x \\) and \\( t \\) in space-time.\n   - The derivatives in PDEs are partial derivatives, meaning they are taken with respect to one of the independent variables while holding the others constant.\n   - PDEs are used to model phenomena that change with respect to multiple variables, such as the diffusion of heat in a solid or the propagation of waves in a medium.\n   - An example of a PDE is the heat equation \\( \\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial t} = \\alpha \\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial x^2} \\), which describes how the temperature \\( u \\) changes over time \\( t \\) and space \\( x \\).\n\nIn summary, the key difference between ODEs and PDEs is that ODEs involve functions of a single independent variable and ordinary derivatives, while PDEs involve functions of multiple independent variables and partial derivatives.",
